# Spec 0022 — Optical Constructor foundation: beam-tree domain model, canonical JSON persistence, and photon-energy units

## 0. Binding constraints (apply to every part)

- **0.1 — Language and platform.** All new code in this spec MUST be F# targeting
  `net10.0`, matching every project already in the solution
  (`Berreman/Berreman.slnx`; e.g. `Berreman/OpticalModel/OpticalModel.fsproj:4`
  pins `<TargetFramework>net10.0</TargetFramework>`). No new language or runtime
  is introduced.
- **0.2 — Reuse the engine, do not fork it.** The new domain model MUST wrap the
  existing engine value types by reference, not re-declare them. The three the
  implementer reaches for first:
  - `IncidentLightInfo` (`Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:338`) — the source's
    wavelength / refraction index / incidence angle / polarization / ellipticity.
  - `OpticalSystem` (`Berreman/Berreman/Media.fs:94`) — a sample's full
    upper / films / substrate / lower stack.
  - `Polarization` (`Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:314`) — a polarizer's /
    analyzer's transmission axis.
- **0.3 — Scope of THIS spec is the foundation only.** This spec delivers three
  things and nothing else: (A) the beam-tree topology domain model, (B) its
  canonical JSON persistence, (C) the photon-energy unit conversions. The
  following are committed product scope (per
  `specs/0022/.manual/010-optical-constructor-spec-and-tech-stack.md`) but are
  **explicitly deferred to later cycles** and MUST NOT be implemented here:
  the Avalonia.FuncUI desktop UI; the materials / dispersion-model library;
  design-synthesis / optimization / inverse-fitting (ALGLIB); the chart layer
  (ScottPlot / Plotly.NET); per-branch field *evaluation / solving*; lens and
  curved-mirror *physics*; the `.binz` bulk-results format.
- **0.4 — Plausible-expansion exclusions.** A downstream implementer is prone to
  adding the following; none are in scope and each MUST be omitted:
  - **No solver invocation.** This spec models and persists topology and
    parameters only. It MUST NOT call `OpticalSystemSolver`
    (`Berreman/Berreman/Solvers.fs:199`) or compute any reflected / transmitted
    field. Wiring evaluation onto the tree is a future cycle.
  - **No change to engine types.** `OpticalSystem`, `IncidentLightInfo`,
    `WaveLength` (`Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:280`), and the `Eps`/`Mu`/`Rho`
    tensors MUST NOT be edited. In particular the `WaveLength` DU MUST NOT be
    extended with an eV case — photon-energy conversion lives in `Constants.fs`
    (Part C) and is applied at the domain/IO boundary.
  - **No caching, retry, async, configuration knobs, versioning shims, or
    backwards-compatibility migration code.** Every persisted document this
    cycle produces is written by this cycle's writer; there is no prior on-disk
    format to migrate from, so the loader starts from a blank slate.
  - **No new optimization / linear-algebra backend.** The math seam stays as it
    is (`Berreman/Berreman/MathNetNumericsMath.fs:3-4`); ALGLIB is a forward
    decision recorded for the deferred optimization cycle, not wired here.

---

## Part A — Beam-tree domain model (CRITICAL — land first)

### A.0 Problem statement

The repository is a strong 1-D Berreman 4×4 transfer-matrix engine: given one
`IncidentLightInfo` and one `OpticalSystem`, `BaseOpticalSystemSolver` already
produces an `EmFieldSystem` holding the **incident, reflected, and transmitted**
fields (`Berreman/Berreman/Solvers.fs:140-147`; `EmFieldSystem` at
`Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:550`). What the engine has no notion of is a
*system of elements*: the central act of an optical-constructor app is to chain
elements (source → polarizer → sample → analyzer → detector) and, because almost
every element emits **both** a reflected and a transmitted beam, to attach
further elements to **either** output. The system is therefore a **tree of
beams**, not a linear chain, and mirrors are the deliberate exception that carry
a reflected branch only.

This part introduces that orchestration/topology layer as a pure F# domain model:
element identity and classification, the branching tree, and the invariants that
make the tree well-formed. It is the foundation every later feature (UI,
evaluation, optimization, persistence of whole projects) hangs off. Per §0.3 it
models structure and parameters only; it performs no solving.

**Interpretation recorded (no question raised).** The preliminary research lists
a broad element palette and many features. The most defensible first deliverable
under this project's minimum-implementation discipline is the topology layer plus
its persistence and units, with evaluation and the UI deferred. Element kinds
whose physics the engine does not yet evaluate (lens, curved mirror) are modelled
as **parameter-carrying nodes** so the palette and the tree are expressible and
serialisable now; their physics is a named later cycle.

**Home project.** The new model lands in the existing, currently-stub
`OpticalModel` project (namespace `Softellect.Berreman.OpticalModel`,
`Berreman/OpticalModel/Primitives.fs:1`, whose body is the placeholder
`let x = 1`). That project today declares no reference to the engine
(`Berreman/OpticalModel/OpticalModel.fsproj` compiles only `Primitives.fs` and
references no other project); A.6 adds the engine reference. Reusing this project
rather than creating a new one honours reuse-before-invention.

### A.1 Define element identity and classification

Add `Berreman/OpticalModel/OpticalElement.fs` declaring, in namespace
`Softellect.Berreman.OpticalModel`:

- An **element id** type `ElementId` wrapping a `System.Guid` (single-case DU),
  with a `create` that takes an explicit `Guid` argument. The constructor MUST
  NOT call `Guid.NewGuid()` internally — id minting is the caller's concern, so
  that construction is deterministic and unit-testable.
- A **mirror classification** DU `ElementClass` with exactly two cases,
  `Mirror` and `NonMirror`. This is the single source of truth for the branching
  rule in A.3.

### A.2 Define the element-kind catalogue

In the same file, declare an `ElementKind` DU enumerating the palette, each case
carrying the minimum parameters needed to describe (not evaluate) the element:

- `LightSource of IncidentLightInfo` — reuse `Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:338`.
- `Polarizer of Polarization` — reuse `Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:314`.
- `Sample of OpticalSystem` — reuse `Berreman/Berreman/Media.fs:94`; this is the
  film / plate / wedge stack the engine already understands.
- `Analyzer of Polarization`.
- `Detector`.
- `Lens of LensParameters` — a net-new record holding front/back radius of
  curvature, clear aperture, a substrate-material reference, and optional
  surface-coating references, all as plain scalars / ids. No optical evaluation.
- `CurvedMirror of CurvedMirrorParameters` — a net-new record holding radius of
  curvature, aperture, and an optional coating reference.

`LensParameters` and `CurvedMirrorParameters` MUST be flat records of primitives
(floats, ids, options); they MUST NOT embed solver state or `OpticalProperties`
tensors. Each new record MUST trace only to the palette named here — no extra
fields beyond curvature/aperture/coating/substrate.

### A.3 Define the optical element and the mirror invariant source

In the same file, declare the `OpticalElement` record:

- `id : ElementId`
- `name : string`
- `kind : ElementKind`
- `elementClass : ElementClass`
- `defaultLengthUnit : LengthUnit` (A.4)
- `defaultSpectralUnit : SpectralUnit option` — `Some` only for a `LightSource`,
  `None` otherwise.

Provide a helper `OpticalElement.isMirror` returning `true` iff
`elementClass = Mirror`. `elementClass` — not the `ElementKind` case — is the
authority for branching, so the operator MAY classify a highly-reflective
`Sample` as a mirror; `CurvedMirror` SHOULD default to `Mirror` at construction.

### A.4 Define per-element units

In `Berreman/OpticalModel/OpticalElement.fs` declare two DUs used as the
per-element default unit (the conversion arithmetic itself is Part C):

- `LengthUnit` with cases `Meter | Millimeter | Micrometer | Nanometer |
  Angstrom`.
- `SpectralUnit` with cases `Nanometer | Micrometer | Angstrom | ElectronVolt |
  Wavenumber` (Wavenumber = cm⁻¹).

These DUs carry no behaviour beyond identifying the unit; they exist so an
element remembers the unit it was authored in (a plate in mm, a film in nm, an
EUV source in eV) while the canonical internal representation stays SI meters as
the engine already requires (`Berreman/Berreman/Constants.fs:27-33`). Conversion
to/from canonical units happens through the Part C functions at the IO boundary.

### A.5 Define the beam tree and enforce the mirror invariant

Add `Berreman/OpticalModel/BeamTree.fs` (namespace
`Softellect.Berreman.OpticalModel`) declaring:

- A recursive `BeamTree` modelling a node and its branches, e.g.
  `BeamTree of OpticalElement * BeamBranches`, where `BeamBranches` is a record
  `{ reflected : BeamTree option; transmitted : BeamTree option }`. A `None`
  branch is an open / terminated beam; a `Some` branch continues with a downstream
  sub-tree.
- A smart constructor (e.g. `BeamTree.create : OpticalElement -> BeamBranches ->
  Result<BeamTree, string>`) that enforces the invariant: **when the element is a
  mirror (`OpticalElement.isMirror`), `transmitted` MUST be `None`**; a mirror
  node with a non-`None` transmitted branch MUST yield `Error` naming the
  violation. A non-mirror element MAY carry either, both, or neither branch.
- A `leaf : OpticalElement -> BeamTree` convenience that builds a node with both
  branches `None` (valid for mirrors and non-mirrors alike).
- An `attach` helper (e.g.
  `attach : RT -> BeamTree -> BeamTree -> Result<BeamTree, string>`) that places a
  sub-tree on the reflected or transmitted branch of a parent and re-checks the
  invariant, reusing the engine's existing `RT` discriminator
  (`Reflected | Transmitted`, `Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:61`) rather than
  introducing a new branch-selector DU.

The model MUST be plain data and total functions only — no reflection, dynamic
dispatch, mutable global state, or runtime metaprogramming. Branch routing MUST
be traceable by reading these two files.

### A.6 Wire the project

Edit `Berreman/OpticalModel/OpticalModel.fsproj` to:

- add a `<ProjectReference Include="..\Berreman\Berreman.fsproj" />` so the
  engine types in §0.2 are in scope;
- add `OpticalElement.fs` and `BeamTree.fs` to the `<Compile>` item group, before
  `Serialization.fs` (Part B), in dependency order.

`Primitives.fs` MUST be left unchanged.

---

## Part B — Canonical JSON persistence

### B.0 Problem statement

A domain model that cannot be saved and reloaded is not usable. The agreed
storage decision is canonical JSON with a published JSON Schema validated on load
(preliminary research Part III §2). This part serialises the Part A `BeamTree` to
canonical JSON and back with round-trip fidelity, and validates documents against
a shipped schema on load. Bulk numeric results (`.binz`) are out of scope (§0.3):
this cycle produces no bulk results to store.

### B.1 Serialization library and converters

Add `Berreman/OpticalModel/Serialization.fs`. The implementer reaches for these
primitives first:

- **`System.Text.Json`** — the serializer core.
- **`FSharp.SystemTextJson`** (Tarmil) — idiomatic F# DU / record / option / list
  serialization; register its `JsonFSharpConverter` on a single shared
  `JsonSerializerOptions`.
- A **`System.Numerics.Complex` converter** — the only leaf type the F# converter
  does not cover, because `Sample of OpticalSystem` reaches `Eps`/`Mu`/`Rho`
  tensors built on `ComplexMatrix3x3` (`Berreman/Berreman/MaterialProperties.fs:59`),
  whose elements are `System.Numerics.Complex`. Serialise each `Complex` as a
  two-field object `{ "re": <number>, "im": <number> }`. F# units-of-measure on
  fields such as `double<nm>` are erased at runtime and serialise as plain
  numbers, so they need no converter.

Expose one shared `options` value and the save / load entry points; do not create
a per-call options instance.

### B.2 Save and load entry points

In `Serialization.fs` provide:

- `BeamTreeDocument.save : string -> BeamTree -> unit` — serialise a tree to the
  canonical document at the given path.
- `BeamTreeDocument.load : string -> Result<BeamTree, string>` — read a document,
  validate it against the schema (B.3), and deserialise; a schema-invalid or
  structurally-invalid document MUST yield `Error` with a message naming the
  offending JSON path, never a partially-constructed tree.

### B.3 Schema and validate-on-load

- Ship a JSON Schema at `Berreman/OpticalModel/schemas/optical-system.schema.json`
  describing the canonical document (the `BeamTree` shape and its element-kind
  union).
- Validate every document against that schema during `load` using
  **`JsonSchema.Net`** before deserialising. The schema file MUST be loaded
  relative to the assembly location (a path resolved from
  `System.Reflection.Assembly` location), not from a hard-coded absolute path.

### B.4 On-disk naming and committable-state check

- The canonical document extension is **`.ocsys.json`** ("optical-constructor
  system"). It was cross-checked against the repository root `.gitignore`: the
  only global content patterns there are `*.[Cc]ache` (`.gitignore:209`), `*.log`
  (`.gitignore:80`), `*.tmp` (`.gitignore:78`), and `/data` (`.gitignore:331`);
  `*.json` and `*.ocsys.json` collide with none of them, so example documents and
  the schema are committable with no `!`-override dance required.
- Ship at least one example document
  `Berreman/OpticalModel/examples/source-sample-detector.ocsys.json` representing a
  source → sample → detector tree, used by the round-trip test (Test artifacts).

---

## Part C — Photon-energy and Ångström units

### C.0 Problem statement

The engine's `Constants.fs` defines the `meter` / `mm` / `mkm` / `nm` measures and
their meter conversions (`Berreman/Berreman/Constants.fs:5-33`) but has no
Ångström, electron-volt, or wavenumber support. EUV / free-electron-laser work is
specified in eV and spectroscopy in cm⁻¹, so the per-element `SpectralUnit`
(A.4) needs these conversions to map to/from the engine's canonical
wavelength-in-meters representation.

### C.1 Add the conversions to `Constants.fs`

Edit `Berreman/Berreman/Constants.fs` (additive only — existing declarations
unchanged) to add:

- An `[<Measure>] type angstrom` and `angstromToMeter : double<meter/angstrom> =
  1.0e-10<meter/angstrom>`, mirroring the existing `nmToMeter` /`mkmToMeter`
  /`mmToMeter` form.
- A photon-energy conversion pair between electron-volts and wavelength in
  nanometres using `E[eV] = 1239.841984 / λ[nm]` (the hc value; the research's
  `1239.84` is the rounded form): `evFromNm : double<nm> -> double` and
  `nmFromEv : double -> double<nm>`.
- A wavenumber conversion pair using `ν̃[cm⁻¹] = 1.0e7 / λ[nm]`:
  `wavenumberFromNm : double<nm> -> double` and `nmFromWavenumber : double ->
  double<nm>`.

These are pure functions / constants. They MUST NOT alter the `WaveLength` DU
(`Berreman/Berreman/Fields.fs:280`) or any solver path (§0.4).

---

## Acceptance criteria

### Part A acceptance
- **AC-A1:** After calling the `BeamTree` smart constructor with a mirror element
  (`elementClass = Mirror`) and a non-`None` `transmitted` branch, the call MUST
  return `Error` naming the mirror-transmitted-branch violation, and MUST NOT
  return a `BeamTree`.
- **AC-A2:** After calling the smart constructor with a non-mirror element, the
  call MUST return `Ok` for every combination of `reflected`/`transmitted` being
  `None` or `Some`.
- **AC-A3:** For any constructed `OpticalElement`, `defaultSpectralUnit` MUST be
  `Some` when `kind` is `LightSource` and `None` for every other kind, and
  `defaultLengthUnit` MUST be present (a `LengthUnit` case) on every element.
- **AC-A4:** The `ElementKind` DU MUST expose the seven cases of A.2;
  `LightSource` MUST wrap `IncidentLightInfo` and `Sample` MUST wrap
  `OpticalSystem` by reference (constructible from the engine values without
  copying their fields).

### Part B acceptance
- **AC-B1:** For any `BeamTree` built via the Part A constructors, `load (save t)`
  MUST return `Ok t'` where `t'` is structurally equal to `t` (round-trip
  identity), including a `Sample of OpticalSystem` node whose `Eps`/`Mu`/`Rho`
  complex entries survive the round trip.
- **AC-B2:** `load` of a document that violates
  `schemas/optical-system.schema.json` MUST return `Error` with a message naming
  the offending JSON path; `load` of the shipped example document MUST return
  `Ok`.
- **AC-B3:** The canonical extension `.ocsys.json` MUST NOT match any global
  content pattern in the root `.gitignore`, so a committed `*.ocsys.json` file is
  tracked by `git` without an override.

### Part C acceptance
- **AC-C1:** `evFromNm` and `nmFromEv` MUST satisfy `E·λ ≈ 1239.841984`
  (eV·nm) and be mutual inverses within a 1e-9 relative tolerance;
  `wavenumberFromNm 500.0<nm>` MUST equal `2.0e4` cm⁻¹ within the same tolerance;
  `angstromToMeter` MUST convert `1.0<angstrom>` to `1.0e-10` m exactly.

## Files in scope
- `Berreman/OpticalModel/OpticalElement.fs` (new) — `ElementId`, `ElementClass`,
  `ElementKind`, `LensParameters`, `CurvedMirrorParameters`, `OpticalElement`,
  `LengthUnit`, `SpectralUnit`.
- `Berreman/OpticalModel/BeamTree.fs` (new) — `BeamTree`, `BeamBranches`, smart
  constructor, `leaf`, `attach`.
- `Berreman/OpticalModel/Serialization.fs` (new) — shared `JsonSerializerOptions`,
  `Complex` converter, `BeamTreeDocument.save` / `.load`, schema validation.
- `Berreman/OpticalModel/schemas/optical-system.schema.json` (new) — canonical
  document schema.
- `Berreman/OpticalModel/examples/source-sample-detector.ocsys.json` (new) —
  example document for the round-trip test.
- `Berreman/OpticalModel/OpticalModel.fsproj` (edit) — add engine
  `ProjectReference`, the three new `Compile` items in dependency order, and the
  `FSharp.SystemTextJson` and `JsonSchema.Net` package references; copy the
  `schemas/` and `examples/` content to output.
- `Berreman/Berreman/Constants.fs` (edit) — add `angstrom` measure and the eV /
  cm⁻¹ / Ångström conversions.
- `Berreman/BerremanTests/BeamTreeTests.fs` (new) — Part A + Part B tests.
- `Berreman/BerremanTests/UnitConversionTests.fs` (new) — Part C tests.
- `Berreman/BerremanTests/BerremanTests.fsproj` (edit) — add a
  `ProjectReference` to `OpticalModel.fsproj` and the two new `Compile` items.

## Test artifacts
